{"id":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/8d2e7574-2890-4e1d-9951-36417068373dv1.0","type":"EvidenceStrengthAssertion","dc:description":"SMARCC1 was first reported in relation to autosomal dominant SMARCC1-associated developmental dysgenesis syndrome in 2018 (Al Mutairi et al., PMID: 29360170). SMARCC1-associated developmental dysgenesis syndrome is characterized by developmental delay, cerebral ventriculomegaly, aqueductal stenosis, and other associated structural brain and cardiac defects. Nine variants (missense, canonical splice site, nonsense, and frameshift) that have been reported in nine probands in four publications (PMIDs: 29360170, 29983323, 33077954, 34906496) are included in this curation. Variants are inherited primarily de novo. More evidence is available in the literature, but the maximum score for genetic evidence (12 pts.) has been reached. The mechanism of pathogenicity is reported to be loss of function. This gene-disease relationship is also supported by expression in the neuroepithelium and ventricular zone during neurogenesis (PMID: 29983323), biochemical function important for the BAF chromatin remodeling complex during human brain morphogenesis (PMID: 36993720), and two homozygous mouse models with brain abnormalities (PMIDs: 11604513, 24170322). In summary, there is definitive evidence supporting the relationship between SMARCC1 and autosomal dominant SMARCC1-associated developmental dysgenesis syndrome. This has been repeatedly demonstrated in both the research and clinical diagnostic settings, and has been upheld over time. This classification was approved by the ClinGen Brain Malformations GCEP on the meeting date April 11, 2023 (SOP Version 9).","dc:isVersionOf":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/8d2e7574-2890-4e1d-9951-36417068373d","GCISnapshot":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/bb13d681-db77-4219-93ce-a9eefbd2839c","calculatedEvidenceStrength":"Definitive","contributions":[{"id":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/